[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Acquiring standard STM topographs at many different tip-sample biases and comparing to experimental topographic information is perhaps the most straightforward spectroscopic method.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] The tip-sample bias can also be changed on a line-by-line basis during a single scan.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] This method creates two interleaved images at different biases.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Since only the states between the Fermi levels of the sample and the tip contribute to I , this method is a quick way to determine whether there are any interesting bias-dependent features on the surface.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] However, only limited information about the electronic structure can be extracted by this method, since the constant I topographs depend on the tip and sample DOS's and the tunneling transmission probability, which depends on the tip-sample spacing, as described in equation (5).
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] By using modulation techniques, a constant current topograph and the spatially resolved $dI/dV$ can be acquired simultaneously.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] A small, high frequency sinusoidal modulation voltage is superimposed on the D.C. tip-sample bias.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] The A.C. component of the tunneling current is recorded using a lock-in amplifier, and the component in-phase with the tip-sample bias modulation gives $dI/dV$ directly.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] The amplitude of the modulation Vm has to be kept smaller than the spacing of the characteristic spectral features.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] The broadening caused by the modulation amplitude is 2 eVm and it has to be added to the thermal broadening of 3.2 kBT.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] In practice, the modulation frequency is chosen slightly higher than the bandwidth of the STM feedback system.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] This choice prevents the feedback control from compensating for the modulation by changing the tip-sample spacing and minimizes the displacement current 90° out-of-phase with the applied bias modulation.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Such effects arise from the capacitance between the tip and the sample, which grows as the modulation frequency increases.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] In order to obtain I-V curves simultaneously with a topograph, a sample-and-hold circuit is used in the feedback loop for the z piezo signal.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] The sample-and-hold circuit freezes the voltage applied to the z piezo, which freezes the tip-sample distance, at the desired location allowing I-V measurements without the feedback system responding.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] The tip-sample bias is swept between the specified values, and the tunneling current is recorded.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] After the spectra acquisition, the tip-sample bias is returned to the scanning value, and the scan resumes.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Using this method, the local electronic structure of semiconductors in the band gap can be probed.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] There are two ways to record I-V curves in the manner described above.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] In constant-spacing scanning tunneling spectroscopy (CS-STS), the tip stops scanning at the desired location to obtain an I-V curve.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] The tip-sample spacing is adjusted to reach the desired initial current, which may be different from the initial current setpoint, at a specified tip-sample bias.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] A sample-and-hold amplifier freezes the z piezo feedback signal, which holds the tip-sample spacing constant by preventing the feedback system from changing the bias applied to the z piezo.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] The tip-sample bias is swept through the specified values, and the tunneling current is recorded.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Either numerical differentiation of I(V) or lock-in detection as described above for modulation techniques can be used to find $dI/dV$ .
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] If lock-in detection is used, then an A.C. modulation voltage is applied to the D.C. tip-sample bias during the bias sweep and the A.C. component of the current in-phase with the modulation voltage is recorded.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] In variable-spacing scanning tunneling spectroscopy (VS-STS), the same steps occur as in CS-STS through turning off the feedback.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] As the tip-sample bias is swept through the specified values, the tip-sample spacing is decreased continuously as the magnitude of the bias is reduced.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Generally, a minimum tip-sample spacing is specified to prevent the tip from crashing into the sample surface at the 0 V tip-sample bias.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Lock-in detection and modulation techniques are used to find the conductivity, because the tunneling current is a function also of the varying tip-sample spacing.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Numerical differentiation of I(V) with respect to V would include the contributions from the varying tip-sample spacing.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Introduced by Mårtensson and Feenstra to allow conductivity measurements over several orders of magnitude, VS-STS is useful for conductivity measurements on systems with large band gaps.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Such measurements are necessary to properly define the band edges and examine the gap for states.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Current-imaging-tunneling spectroscopy (CITS) is an STS technique where an I-V curve is recorded at each pixel in the STM topograph.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Either variable-spacing or constant-spacing spectroscopy may be used to record the I-V curves.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] The conductance, $dI/dV$ , can be obtained by numerical differentiation of I with respect to V or acquired using lock-in detection as described above.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Because the topographic image and the tunneling spectroscopy data are obtained nearly simultaneously, there is nearly perfect registry of topographic and spectroscopic data.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] As a practical concern, the number of pixels in the scan or the scan area may be reduced to prevent piezo creep or thermal drift from moving the feature of study or the scan area during the duration of the scan.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] While most CITS data obtained on the times scale of several minutes, some experiments may require stability over longer periods of time.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] One approach to improving the experimental design is by applying feature-oriented scanning (FOS) methodology.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] From the obtained I-V curves, the band gap of the sample at the location of the I-V measurement can be determined.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] By plotting the magnitude of I on a log scale versus the tip-sample bias, the band gap can clearly be determined.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Although determination of the band gap is possible from a linear plot of the I-V curve, the log scale increases the sensitivity.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Alternatively, a plot of the conductance, $dI/dV$ , versus the tip-sample bias, V, allows one to locate the band edges that determine the band gap.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] The structure in the $dI/dV$ , as a function of the tip-sample bias, is associated with the density of states of the surface when the tip-sample bias is less than the work functions of the tip and the sample.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Usually, the WKB approximation for the tunneling current is used to interpret these measurements at low tip-sample bias relative to the tip and sample work functions.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] where $\rho _{s}$ is the sample density of states, $\rho _{t}$ is the tip density of states, and T is the tunneling transmission probability.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Although the tunneling transmission probability T is generally unknown, at a fixed location T increases smoothly and monotonically with the tip-sample bias in the WKB approximation.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Hence, structure in the $dI/dV$ is usually assigned to features in the density of states in the first term of equation (7).
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Interpretation of $dI/dV$ as a function of position is more complicated, but can reveal information about the momentum-space electronic structure from Quasiparticle interference imaging.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Spatial variations in T show up in measurements of $dI/dV$ as an inverted topographic background.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] When obtained in constant current mode, images of the spatial variation of $dI/dV$ contain a convolution of topographic and electronic structure.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] An additional complication arises since $dI/dV=I/V$ in the low-bias limit.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Thus, $dI/dV$ diverges as V approaches 0, preventing investigation of the local electronic structure near the Fermi level.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Since both the tunneling current, equation (5), and the conductance, equation (7), depend on the tip DOS and the tunneling transition probability, T, quantitative information about the sample DOS is very difficult to obtain.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Additionally, the voltage dependence of T, which is usually unknown, can vary with position due to local fluctuations in the electronic structure of the surface.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] For some cases, normalizing $dI/dV$ by dividing by $I/V$ can minimize the effect of the voltage dependence of T and the influence of the tip-sample spacing.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Feenstra et al. argued that the dependencies of $T\left(E,eV,r\right)$ and $T\left(eV,eV,r\right)$ on tip-sample spacing and tip-sample bias tend to cancel, since they appear as ratios.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] where $B\left(V\right)$ normalizes T to the DOS and $A\left(V\right)$ describes the influence of the electric field in the tunneling gap on the decay length.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Under the assumption that $A\left(V\right)$ and $B\left(V\right)$ vary slowly with tip-sample bias, the features in $\left(dI/dV\right)/\left(I/V\right)$ reflect the sample DOS, $\rho _{s}$ .
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] While STS can provide spectroscopic information with amazing spatial resolution, there are some limitations.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] The STM and STS lack chemical sensitivity.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Since the tip-sample bias range in tunneling experiments is limited to $\pm \phi /e$ , where $\phi$ is the apparent barrier height, STM and STS only sample valence electron states.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Element-specific information is generally impossible to extract from STM and STS experiments, since the chemical bond formation greatly perturbs the valence states.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] At finite temperatures, the thermal broadening of the electron energy distribution due to the Fermi-distribution limits spectroscopic resolution.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Hence, the total energy deviation is $\Delta E\approx 0.1\,\mathrm {eV}$ .
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] where $E_{F}$ is the Fermi energy, $E_{0}$ is the bottom of the valence band, $k_{F}$ is the Fermi wave vector, and r is the lateral resolution.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Since spatial resolution depends on the tip-sample spacing, smaller tip-sample spacings and higher topographic resolution blur the features in tunneling spectra.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/scanning-tunneling-spectroscopy] Despite these limitations, STS and STM provide the possibility for probing the local electronic structure of metals, semiconductors, and thin insulators on a scale unobtainable with other spectroscopic methods.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] In solid-state physics, the **work function** (sometimes spelled **workfunction**) is the minimum thermodynamic work (i.e., energy) needed to remove an electron from a solid to a point in the vacuum immediately outside the solid surface.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Here "immediately" means that the final electron position is far from the surface on the atomic scale, but still too close to the solid to be influenced by ambient electric fields in the vacuum.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The work function is not a characteristic of a bulk material, but rather a property of the surface of the material (depending on crystal face and contamination).
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] where −*e* is the charge of an electron, *ϕ* is the electrostatic potential in the vacuum nearby the surface, and *E*F is the Fermi level (electrochemical potential of electrons) inside the material.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The term −*eϕ* is the energy of an electron at rest in the vacuum nearby the surface.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] In practice, one directly controls *E*F by the voltage applied to the material through electrodes, and the work function is generally a fixed characteristic of the surface material.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Consequently, this means that when a voltage is applied to a material, the electrostatic potential *ϕ* produced in the vacuum will be somewhat lower than the applied voltage, the difference depending on the work function of the material surface.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] where *V* = −*E*F / *e* is the voltage of the material (as measured by a voltmeter, through an attached electrode), relative to an electrical ground that is defined as having zero Fermi level.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The fact that *ϕ* depends on the material surface means that the space between two dissimilar conductors will have a built-in electric field, when those conductors are in total equilibrium with each other (electrically shorted to each other, and with equal temperatures).
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The work function refers to removal of an electron to a position that is far enough from the surface (many nm) that the force between the electron and its image charge in the surface can be neglected.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The electron must also be close to the surface compared to the nearest edge of a crystal facet, or to any other change in the surface structure, such as a change in the material composition, surface coating or reconstruction.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The built-in electric field that results from these structures, and any other ambient electric field present in the vacuum are excluded in defining the work function.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] are critical parameters in determining the amount of current that can be emitted.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] , the common choice for vacuum tube filaments, can survive to high temperatures but its emission is somewhat limited due to its relatively high work function (approximately 4.5 eV).
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] ), the emission can be greatly increased.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] in the junctions of differing materials, such as metals, semiconductors, and insulators.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] , are based on the thought experiment of two materials coming together in vacuum, such that the surfaces charge up and adjust their work functions to become equal just before contact.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] In reality these work function heuristics are inaccurate due to their neglect of numerous microscopic effects.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] However, they provide a convenient estimate until the true value can be determined by experiment.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Variation in work function between different surfaces causes a non-uniform electrostatic potential in the vacuum.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] known as patch potentials are always present due to microscopic inhomogeneities.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Critical apparatus may have surfaces covered with molybdenum, which shows low variations in work function between different crystal faces.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] If two conducting surfaces are moved relative to each other, and there is potential difference in the space between them, then an electric current will be driven.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] on a conductor depends on the magnitude of the electric field, which in turn depends on the distance between the surfaces.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The externally observed electrical effects are largest when the conductors are separated by the smallest distance without touching (once brought into contact, the charge will instead flow internally through the junction between the conductors).
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Since two conductors in equilibrium can have a built-in potential difference due to work function differences, this means that bringing dissimilar conductors into contact, or pulling them apart, will drive electric currents.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] These contact currents can damage sensitive microelectronic circuitry and occur even when the conductors would be grounded in the absence of motion.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Certain physical phenomena are highly sensitive to the value of the work function.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The observed data from these effects can be fitted to simplified theoretical models, allowing one to extract a value of the work function.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] These phenomenologically extracted work functions may be slightly different from the thermodynamic definition given above.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] For inhomogeneous surfaces, the work function varies from place to place, and different methods will yield different values of the typical "work function" as they average or select differently among the microscopic work functions.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Many techniques have been developed based on different physical effects to measure the electronic work function of a sample.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] One may distinguish between two groups of experimental methods for work function measurements: absolute and relative.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The work function is important in the theory of thermionic emission, where thermal fluctuations provide enough energy to "evaporate" electrons out of a hot material (called the 'emitter') into the vacuum.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] If these electrons are absorbed by another, cooler material (called the *collector*) then a measurable electric current will be observed.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Thermionic emission can be used to measure the work function of both the hot emitter and cold collector.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Generally, these measurements involve fitting to Richardson's law, and so they must be carried out in a low temperature and low current regime where space charge effects are absent.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] determined simply by the thermionic work function of the emitter.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] If an electric field is applied towards the surface of the emitter, then all of the escaping electrons will be accelerated away from the emitter and absorbed into whichever material is applying the electric field.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] where *k* is the Boltzmann constant and the proportionality constant *A*e is the Richardson's constant of the emitter.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] In this case, the dependence of *J*e on *T*e can be fitted to yield *W*e.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The same setup can be used to instead measure the work function in the collector, simply by adjusting the applied voltage.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] If an electric field is applied *away from* the emitter instead, then most of the electrons coming from the emitter will simply be reflected back to the emitter.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Only the highest energy electrons will have enough energy to reach the collector, and the height of the potential barrier in this case depends on the collector's work function, rather than the emitter's.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The current is still governed by Richardson's law.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] However, in this case the barrier height does not depend on *W*e.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] where *W*c is the collector's thermionic work function, Δ*V*ce is the applied collector–emitter voltage, and Δ*V*S is the Seebeck voltage in the hot emitter (the influence of Δ*V*S is often omitted, as it is a small contribution of order 10 mV).
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] where *A* is a Richardson-type constant that depends on the collector material but may also depend on the emitter material, and the diode geometry.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] In this case, the dependence of *J*c on *T*e, or on Δ*V*ce, can be fitted to yield *W*c.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] This **retarding potential method** is one of the simplest and oldest methods of measuring work functions, and is advantageous since the measured material (collector) is not required to survive high temperatures.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The photoelectric work function is the minimum photon energy required to liberate an electron from a substance, in the photoelectric effect.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] If the photon's energy is greater than the substance's work function, photoelectric emission occurs and the electron is liberated from the surface.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Similar to the thermionic case described above, the liberated electrons can be extracted into a collector and produce a detectable current, if an electric field is applied into the surface of the emitter.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Excess photon energy results in a liberated electron with non-zero kinetic energy.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] where *W*e is the work function of the emitter.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Photoelectric measurements require a great deal of care, as an incorrectly designed experimental geometry can result in an erroneous measurement of work function.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] This may be responsible for the large variation in work function values in scientific literature.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Moreover, the minimum energy can be misleading in materials where there are no actual electron states at the Fermi level that are available for excitation.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] For example, in a semiconductor the minimum photon energy would actually correspond to the valence band edge rather than work function.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Of course, the photoelectric effect may be used in the retarding mode, as with the thermionic apparatus described above.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] In the retarding case, the dark collector's work function is measured instead.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The Kelvin probe technique relies on the detection of an electric field (gradient in *ϕ*) between a sample material and probe material.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The electric field can be varied by the voltage Δ*V*sp that is applied to the probe relative to the sample.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Since the experimenter controls and knows Δ*V*sp, then finding the flat vacuum condition gives directly the work function difference between the two materials.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The only question is, how to detect the flat vacuum condition?
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Typically, the electric field is detected by varying the distance between the sample and probe.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] When the distance is changed but Δ*V*sp is held constant, a current will flow due to the change in capacitance.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] This current is proportional to the vacuum electric field, and so when the electric field is neutralized no current will flow.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Although the Kelvin probe technique only measures a work function difference, it is possible to obtain an absolute work function by first calibrating the probe against a reference material (with known work function) and then using the same probe to measure a desired sample.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The Kelvin probe technique can be used to obtain work function maps of a surface with extremely high spatial resolution, by using a sharp tip for the probe (see Kelvin probe force microscope).
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The work function depends on the configurations of atoms at the surface of the material.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] For example, on polycrystalline silver the work function is 4.26 eV, but on silver crystals it varies for different crystal faces as (100) face: 4.64 eV, (110) face: 4.52 eV, (111) face: 4.74 eV.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Ranges for typical surfaces are shown in the table below.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Due to the complications described in the modelling section below, it is difficult to theoretically predict the work function with accuracy.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] However, various trends have been identified.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The work function tends to be smaller for metals with an open lattice, and larger for metals in which the atoms are closely packed.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] It is somewhat higher on dense crystal faces than open crystal faces, also depending on surface reconstructions for the given crystal face.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The work function is not simply dependent on the "internal vacuum level" inside the material (i.e., its average electrostatic potential), because of the formation of an atomic-scale electric double layer at the surface.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] This surface electric dipole gives a jump in the electrostatic potential between the material and the vacuum.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] A variety of factors are responsible for the surface electric dipole.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Even with a completely clean surface, the electrons can spread slightly into the vacuum, leaving behind a slightly positively charged layer of material.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] This primarily occurs in metals, where the bound electrons do not encounter a hard wall potential at the surface but rather a gradual ramping potential due to image charge attraction.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The amount of surface dipole depends on the detailed layout of the atoms at the surface of the material, leading to the variation in work function for different crystal faces.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] In a semiconductor, the work function is sensitive to the doping level at the surface of the semiconductor.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Since the doping near the surface can also be controlled by electric fields, the work function of a semiconductor is also sensitive to the electric field in the vacuum.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The reason for the dependence is that, typically, the vacuum level and the conduction band edge retain a fixed spacing independent of doping.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] This spacing is called the electron affinity (note that this has a different meaning than the electron affinity of chemistry); in silicon for example the electron affinity is 4.05 eV.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] From this one might expect that by doping the bulk of the semiconductor, the work function can be tuned.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] In reality, however, the energies of the bands near the surface are often pinned to the Fermi level, due to the influence of surface states.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] If there is a large density of surface states, then the work function of the semiconductor will show a very weak dependence on doping or electric field.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] Theoretical modeling of the work function is difficult, as an accurate model requires a careful treatment of both electronic many body effects and surface chemistry; both of these topics are already complex in their own right.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] One of the earliest successful models for metal work function trends was the jellium model, which allowed for oscillations in electronic density nearby the abrupt surface (these are similar to Friedel oscillations) as well as the tail of electron density extending outside the surface.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] This model showed why the density of conduction electrons (as represented by the Wigner–Seitz radius *rs*) is an important parameter in determining work function.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The jellium model is only a partial explanation, as its predictions still show significant deviation from real work functions.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] More recent models have focused on including more accurate forms of electron exchange and correlation effects, as well as including the crystal face dependence (this requires the inclusion of the actual atomic lattice, something that is neglected in the jellium model).
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] The electron behavior in metals varies with temperature and is largely reflected by the electron work function.
[src:scanning-tunneling-microscopy/work-function] A theoretical model for predicting the temperature dependence of the electron work function, developed by Rahemi et al. explains the underlying mechanism and predicts this temperature dependence for various crystal structures via calculable and measurable parameters.
